					<h2>My essays</h2>
					<p>
						My last posts depend on each other, and should be read in sequence. Articles not in bold are optional
					</p>
					<ul>
						<li><p><a class="bold" href="">Assignment Statment Considered Harmfull</a>. Pervasive mutable state make programs more difficult to deal with. While this is old news, most programmers don't know or don't care. It's a pitty, because <a href="">simple remedies</a> exist.</p>
						</li>
						<li><p><a class="bold" href="">Defining Syntactic Sugar</a>. I somtimes hear arguements about what is or is not syntactic sugar. This is an attempt at defining it.</p>
						</li>
						<li><p><a class="bold" href="">Class-based Programming as Syntactic Sugar</a>. Most of the time, "Object Oriented" actually means classes. Classes are nothing more than syntactic sugar, at least in statically typed languages such as Java and C++. Sugar is not useless, but seeing past it helps us understand classes better.</p>
						</li>
						<li><p><a href="">Taboo "OO"</a>. The term "OO" is so overloaded that we should stop using it. Better substitutes are "classes" and "prototypes".</p>
						</li>
						<li><p><a class="bold" href="">How Class bases Programming Sucks</a> Classes are vastly sub-optimal. Functional programming is far better.</p>
						</li>
					</ul>
